   //Our constructor will open up a connection to our database when created (as soon after creating an instance) — in other words: it's initializing us with all of its resources. We can put code inside here that makes sure we have everything needed for this new session - like the driver, URL etc
   public SessionManager() { //constructor name should be same as class and is necessary because each constructor has a different number/type parameters in Java when you define your classes — these are not optional (it's just considered good practice to provide all details) but they cannot have any other code inside them like methods or constructors
      try { //try block for database connection, it will be executed if the above line is successful. If we get an exception here then control goes back into our catch statement where this error gets printed out and no further codes are processed (it's how you handle exceptions in Java) — again to do with your comments
         Class.forName(DB_DRIVER); //Here, 'Class', is a predefined class that represents all classes used by the application at any given time or until runtime and allows us load information about these pre-defined (i.e., abstract) classes into our Java Virtual Machine for running processes — it does not execute but we use this to get details of existing 'abstract' Classes in a particular context
         connection = DriverManager.getConnection(DB_URL, USERNAME, PASSWORD); //This will connect us with the database (it doesn’t start any actual interaction) by getting an open handle on our pre-configured connections to it — this is where we make sure that once a session has started and 'closed' out after finished processing all interactions or queries in transactions.
         statement = connection.createStatement(); //This will create us with the necessary tools for creating, deleting records etc using SQL statements (it doesn’t begin any actual interaction) — it is used to manage our database interactively via these methods and then we close them off when done interacting by calling 'close' on this statement
      } catch(ClassNotFoundException ex) { //Catch block for handling the case where DriverManager or connection cannot be found in java.classpath (it throws an exception if class not present).  It is a separate section from above, to handle any Class related errors like MySQL database driver classes missing etc which are thrown at runtime
         System.out.println("Class Not Found : " + ex); //Here we print out the error message about what's wrong (the name of exception class) if 'ex', it is an instance present in java, not found — this prints to console and doesn’t stop our program execution like other catch blocks
      }//end try-catch block for database connection setup. It can throw ClassNotFoundException when MySQL JDBC Driver isn't available or misconfigured otherwise the rest of code inside it will be executed in a 'try'-block fashion — these are handled by Java’s way to handle exceptions effectively
   }//end constructor class SessionManager, with all details about database connection setup. No methods yet implemented so far because we only have information and no implementation defined at this point according how our session manager should interact & manage db interactions using prepared statements or something similar in parameterized queries — these will be added as per requirements
